WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.004
A beautiful crust is worthless if nobody can afford it. So

2
00:00:03.104 --> 00:00:05.520
we build the cost from the ground up, and ask a

3
00:00:05.620 --> 00:00:08.624
blunt question — is it cheaper than what people use today?

4
00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:13.144
Each prong has its own bill: fermentation for the polymer, feedstock

5
00:00:13.244 --> 00:00:16.535
and enzyme for the cementing, and alginate we simply buy in.

6
00:00:17.433 --> 00:00:21.012
Now plot cost against the area you treat. Conventional methods

7
00:00:21.112 --> 00:00:24.869
start cheap but climb steeply. Our biological crust starts higher

8
00:00:24.969 --> 00:00:27.599
— the setup costs — but grows far more slowly.

9
00:00:30.066 --> 00:00:33.036
Where the two lines cross is the crossover: beyond that

10
00:00:33.136 --> 00:00:36.497
treated area, the biological option is simply the cheaper one.

11
00:00:36.566 --> 00:00:39.560
And because the cementing locks away carbon dioxide, the

12
00:00:39.660 --> 00:00:42.709
credit for that capture pulls the crossover earlier still

13
00:00:42.809 --> 00:00:44.642
— the crust pays for itself sooner.

